<div id="review_133018151" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/133018151" />
    <a title="Finooola" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2112772-finooola"><img alt="Finooola" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1536096048p2/2112772.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/133018151?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Finooola" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Finooola" href="/user/show/2112772-finooola">Finooola</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2112772-finooola?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer133018151" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8718300144561142030">I liked this book, but have to give it the the 3-star-treatment thanks to a feeling of ambiguity and loose ends I got from it. Don&apos;t get me wrong, I enjoyed certain ambiguous aspects of it, for example the way it was impossible to fix it in an analogous period in history. What I didn&apos;t like was the feeling that the characters were symbolic, and that I didn&apos;t grasp of what. In that sense, maybe the book was a bit too smart for me, and if that&apos;s the case then I am at fault *hangs head*. However, a</span>
  <span id="freeText8718300144561142030" style="display:none">I liked this book, but have to give it the the 3-star-treatment thanks to a feeling of ambiguity and loose ends I got from it. Don't get me wrong, I enjoyed certain ambiguous aspects of it, for example the way it was impossible to fix it in an analogous period in history. What I didn't like was the feeling that the characters were symbolic, and that I didn't grasp of what. In that sense, maybe the book was a bit too smart for me, and if that's the case then I am at fault *hangs head*. However, another thing that bugged me was even though the book was fantastical in so many (unexplained!) ways, the everyday goings on felt very much like a soap opera, or worse, real life. The outlandish things that happen in this book may not happen in everyday life, but anyone on earth, unless they have literally no family, would recognise and roll their eyes at a lot of the feuding in the story. There is nothing wrong with books about the wrangles of everyday families of course, it's just that I don't go out of my way to read them, and was not expecting this to be one. About the loose ends, for the first 200 or so pages I was waiting for the book to click into place, before realising it was never going to. Again, I am at odds with some of the reviews I read so maybe I just didn't get it. I'm going around in circles insulting then making excuses for the book, but I have to finish by saying this book sets out to be an adult fairy tale. Not adult in the xxx sense just to be clear. And as such the characters should be larger than life and somewhat inexplicable, as well the events. I got that, and appreciated it, it just didn't work on the whole for me. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8718300144561142030" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


